2","1475":"1475","1474":"1474","16 October 1542":"16 oktober 1542","about 1474":"circa 1474","1528":"1528","1527":"1527","Lavenham, Suffolk, England":"Lavenham, Suffolk, England","Melford, Suffolkshire, England":"Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Long Melford, Suffolk, England":"Long Melford, Suffolk, England",", , England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"England","Sudbury, Suffolk, England":"Sudbury, Suffolk, England"},"en":{"1459–16 October 1542":"1459–16 October 1542","1450–1527":"1450–1527","1474–1524":"1474–1524","1475–1528":"1475–1528","1459–1542":"1459–1542","22 September 1542":"22 September 1542","13 March 1475":"13 March 1475","1450":"1450","22 April 1528":"22 April 1528","22 April 1527":"22 April 1527","1459":"1459","1524":"1524","1542":"1542","1475":"1475","1474":"1474","16 October 1542":"16 October 1542","about 1474":"about 1474","1528":"1528","1527":"1527","Lavenham, Suffolk, England":"Lavenham, Suffolk, England","Melford, Suffolkshire, England":"Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Long Melford, Suffolk, England":"Long Melford, Suffolk, England",", , England":"England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Sudbury, Suffolk, England":"Sudbury, Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Littlefield","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Littlefield Green in White Waltham, Berkshire. The placename derives from Old English <i>lȳtel</i> ‘little’ + <i>feld</i> ‘open country’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Johanna","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["feminine form of <i>Johannes</i> (  see  John  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Johannah","meanings":["feminine form of <i>Johannes</i> (  see  John  )."]},{"name":"Jonna","meanings":["contracted form of   Johanna ."]},{"name":"Jane","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Johanna Littlefield was born in 1459, in Suffolk, England, United Kingdom. She married Sir John Hammond III about 1474, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died on 16 October 1542, in Lavenham, Suffolk, England, at the age of 83, and was buried in England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1459–16 October 1542":"1459–16. oktoober 1542","1450–1527":"1450–1527","1474–1524":"1474–1524","1475–1528":"1475–1528","1459–1542":"1459–1542","22 September 1542":"22. september 1542","13 March 1475":"13. märts 1475","1450":"1450","22 April 1528":"22. aprill 1528","22 April 1527":"22. aprill 1527","1459":"1459","1524":"1524","1542":"1542","1475":"1475","1474":"1474","16 Octob